name: 4,6-diphenylthieno[3,4-d]-1,3-dioxol-2-one 5,5-dioxide
Reason: 4,6-diphenylthieno[3,4-d]-1,3-dioxol-2-one 5,5-dioxide has a melting point that we will compare to benzene, which has a melting point of 5.5°C (according to the CRC Handbook of Chemistry and Physics, 49th Edition, 1968-1969). The structural modifications we need to consider are the presence of two additional phenyl rings and a thienyl group. Phenyl groups, when connected to a benzene ring, tend to increase the melting point due to the enhancement of the crystalline structure and the increase in molecular weight. The thienyl group introduces a rigid structure and potential hydrogen bonding, which may also contribute to the melting point. Each additional phenyl group can be estimated to add approximately 100°C to the melting point due to increased pi-pi interactions, rigidity, and molecular weight. The thienyl group may also contribute around +20 to +30°C due to its rigid structure and potential hydrogen bonding.
